MEDIUM|internal/fanout/resume.go:413|RebuildPool appends a roster agent's AgentStatus unconditionally but only merges its findings when stream.ParseSource succeeds (the `if perr == nil` guard). A completed (status ok) agent whose findings.txt is unparseable/corrupt is still counted as Succeeded with its old FindingsCount, while its findings are silently dropped from the rebuilt merged findings.txt and summary.TotalFindings — with no error and no log line. Unique to the resume path: fresh WritePool builds findings from in-memory Results, never re-parsing from disk, so a resumed review's aggregate can quietly diverge from the original.|In RebuildPool's per-agent loop, when os.ReadFile succeeds but ParseSource returns an error, emit a structured Warn (agent + path) rather than silently skipping, or treat it as a hard failure for that roster member. Add a test that corrupts one completed agent's findings.txt and asserts ExecuteResume logs/errors instead of producing a short merged set.|correctness|60|internal/fanout/resume.go:404-418|claude
MEDIUM|cmd/atcr/resume.go:149|runResume's graceful-interrupt branch prints the human stderr notice and returns the coded error but, unlike the fresh path, does NOT emit log.FromContext(ctx).Warn("review interrupted by signal"). review.go:205-212 deliberately mirrors the stderr notice as a structured, review_id-correlated Warn so an interrupted run leaves a greppable log record. The resume path correlates its ctx with the review id earlier but then drops that observability on the most important failure event, so monitoring/CI grepping logs for interrupted resumes finds nothing (breaks the AC9/AC10 greppability parity).|Add log.FromContext(ctx).Warn("review interrupted by signal") immediately before the stderr Fprint in runResume's ctx.Canceled branch, mirroring review.go:209. Verify by asserting a Warn record carrying the review_id attribute is emitted when ctx is canceled during a resumed fan-out.|maintainability|15|cmd/atcr/resume.go:147-153 vs cmd/atcr/review.go:205-212|claude
LOW|cmd/atcr/resume.go:58|runResume fail-closes on --fail-on/--verify/--require-verified with an explicit "a CI pipeline could false-PASS" rationale, but --fresh, --thorough, and --min-severity (which exist only to tune the --verify stage) are accepted silently and discarded. A user running `atcr review --resume latest --thorough` gets no feedback that the flag did nothing; the author's own silent-ignore-is-dangerous reasoning applies here too, so the rejection set is internally inconsistent.|Extend the rejection loop to include fresh, thorough, min-severity (all inert without --verify, which is already rejected). Add a table test asserting each of these combined with --resume returns exit 2.|error-handling|15|cmd/atcr/resume.go:56-62|claude
LOW|internal/fanout/resume.go:395|RebuildPool and CompletedAgents key the on-disk index by agentDirName(agent) basename with no duplicate guard, while the fresh WritePool path explicitly rejects two agents collapsing to the same sanitized basename (artifacts.go). If a roster contains two names that sanitize to the same basename, onDisk[dirName] maps both to one directory, corrupting the union tally (double-counted or mis-attributed status).|Add the same seen[dirName] duplicate-rejection in RebuildPool that WritePool has, or assert roster-name uniqueness-after-sanitization once in PrepareResume. Add a test with two roster names sharing a basename.|correctness|30|internal/fanout/resume.go:385-403|claude
LOW|internal/fanout/resume.go:323|ExecuteResume finalizes the manifest with m.Interrupted=interrupted and returns immediately if WriteManifest fails, with no best-effort fallback. ExecuteReview has a deliberate failure-summary + best-effort manifest fallback for the analogous WritePool-succeeded-but-WriteManifest-failed case. If a resume is itself interrupted (AC7) and this final manifest write fails, the on-disk manifest carries the original run's Interrupted value and the new partial state is lost — contradicting the function's own "stays interrupted" promise.|On the RebuildPool-success path, if WriteManifest fails while interrupted is true, fall back to a best-effort marker write (or log loudly) before returning, mirroring review.go ExecuteReview. Verify by injecting a manifest-write failure under interruption.|error-handling|30|internal/fanout/resume.go:317-325|claude
LOW|internal/fanout/resume.go:132|agentStatusName returns ok=false identically for a read error, a JSON unmarshal error, a non-OK status, and an empty Agent field. The "re-running is always safe" rationale is correct, but a corrupt status.json on disk produces zero operator signal: the agent silently re-runs (hitting a provider, cost+latency) with no warning that on-disk state was unreadable, hiding a real anomaly distinct from a legitimately-pending agent.|Keep the fail-safe behavior but emit a structured Warn (with path) when os.ReadFile or json.Unmarshal fails in agentStatusName, so corruption is greppable. Add a test asserting a log line on a corrupt status.json.|error-handling|30|internal/fanout/resume.go:127-145|claude
LOW|internal/fanout/resume.go:482|reviewStageFromStatuses is a near-verbatim copy of reviewStageFor (one over []AgentStatus, one over []Result) with subtly different slice-aliasing shapes. Any future change to the manifest review-stage classification rule must be made in two places and the two can silently diverge.|Define one classifier over a small interface exposing ToolsRequested/ToolsDegraded/Agent and call it from both reviewStageFromStatuses and reviewStageFor. Verify both manifest paths produce identical ReviewStage for equivalent inputs.|maintainability|30|internal/fanout/resume.go:482-501 vs internal/fanout/review.go:711-728|claude
LOW|cmd/atcr/resume.go:109|The correlate-review-id + install-redactor + post-fan-out interrupt-check block is copy-pasted between runReview (review.go) and runResume (resume.go) and has ALREADY drifted (the missing interrupt Warn and an inlined vs hoisted redact root). Two near-identical critical paths that have drifted are a maintenance liability: the next redaction/interrupt change must be made in two places.|Extract a shared correlateAndRedact(ctx,id,repo) helper and a shared reportInterrupt(cmd,ctx,result,prep) that does Warn + stderr notice + coded error; call both from runReview and runResume. Verify both paths still produce identical Warn records and exit codes.|maintainability|60|cmd/atcr/resume.go:109-153 vs cmd/atcr/review.go:183-212|claude
